POLIOMYELITIS UPDATE (32): WILD POLIOVIRUS TYPE 1 ACUTE FLACCID PARALYSIS (PAKISTAN)
************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 27 Jul 2022
Source: The Friday Times [Edited)
https://www.thefridaytimes.com/2022/07/27/fresh-polio-case-detected-in-north-waziristan/


Pakistan has recorded a new case of poliovirus in the North Waziristan district [Khyber Pakhtunkhwa], taking this year's [2022] overall tally to 14.

The Pakistan Polio Laboratory said that the 8-month-old girl, who is the fresh victim, had onset of paralysis on [30 Jun 2022].

According to the health ministry, all 14 cases were reported in children under 2 years of age.

Polio is a highly infectious disease caused by poliovirus mainly affecting children under the age of 5 years. It invades the nervous system and can cause paralysis or even death.

Anti-polio campaigns have proven successful worldwide, with over 99 per cent of the world now polio-free. However, Pakistan and Afghanistan are still polio-endemic and have reported 15 cases, with one being registered in the war-torn country.

The ministry said that the national emergency operations centres of the 2 countries are continuing cross-border coordination efforts.

"The countries have synchronised 2 polio campaigns in May and June [2022] and are ensuring vaccination of children under 10 years of age on all major transit points, along with vaccinating all ages at the international borders," it added.

Last month [June 2022], Federal Health Minister Abdul Qadir Patel asked the people to ensure the administration of anti-polio drops to their children.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[Of the 14 confirmed cases of AFP associated with infection with the WPV1 in Pakistan in 2022, 13 were from North Waziristan. On 22 Jul 2022, a case from Lakki Marwat was confirmed, suggesting that the WPV1 was being transmitted outside of North Waziristan (both districts are in Southern Khyber Pakhtunkhwa). Since April 2022 there has been a new case of WPV1 associated AFP confirmed in Southern Khyber Pakhtunkhwa almost every week.

This case now makes a total of 17 cases of WPV1 associated AFP confirmed in 2022 -- 14 in Pakistan, 1 in Afghanistan, 1 in Malawi, and 1 in Mozambique.

ProMED map of Pakistan: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8704718,2139.
A map showing the districts of Pakistan can be found at https://reliefweb.int/map/pakistan/pakistan-districts-map-03-december-2018. - Mod.MPP]
